Here are the complete steps to create a GitHub repo from a local folder:

Step 1 — Create the repo on GitHub:
Go to https://github.com/new, name it, set it to Private, and do NOT initialize with any files. Click Create repository.

Step 2 — Navigate to your local folder:

cd R:\CHERP_Shares2\Weiner_Mark\DBMGMT\Roberts\aaa_desktop\code_other\git\repository1\copilot

This sets your terminal to the folder you want to turn into a repo.

Step 3 — Initialize Git:

git init

This creates a .git folder, making it a Git repository.

Step 4 — Link to your GitHub repo:

git remote add origin https://github.com/cbrentroberts5/copilot.git

This connects your local folder to the remote GitHub repository.

Step 5 — Stage all files:

git add .

This tells Git to track all files in the folder.

Step 6 — Commit the files:

git commit -m "Initial commit"

This saves a snapshot of your staged files with a message.

Step 7 — Rename the branch to main:

git branch -M main

GitHub uses "main" as the default branch name. This renames "master" to "main".

Step 8 — Push to GitHub:

git push -u origin main

This uploads your commit to GitHub. The -u flag sets "origin main" as the default so future pushes only need "git push".
